Lechelade Gloustershire":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"aproximadamente 1105–":"about 1105–Deceased","1105–Male":"1105–Deceased","1105–Female":"1105–Deceased","1125–Male":"1125–Deceased","1127–Male":"1127–Deceased","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","1085–Female":"1085–Deceased","1080":"1080","before 1125":"before 1125","1127":"1127","1105":"1105","1104":"1104","1125":"1125","about 1127":"about 1127","about 1125":"about 1125","aproximadamente 1105":"about 1105","1085":"1085","The Lennox, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"The Lennox, Dunbartonshire, Scotland","England":"England","Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Lechelade Gloustershire":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leca","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Luis, Jose, Segundo, Miguel, Arturo, Juan, Roberto, Angel, Fernando, Florencio, Francisco.","Galician: habitational name from Lema in A Coruña province, Galicia (Spain).","Amerindian (Ecuador): Cañari name, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Lemma","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Ethiopian Bekele, Mengistu, Seble, Aklilu, Amare, Ayele, Derege, Getachew, Girmai, Hirut, Kebede, Mekonnen.  Italian Cosmo, Massimo, Angelo, Carmine, Nicola, Sisto, Valentino.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Lemma</i>, feminine equivalent of   Lemmo  , from <i>Guglielma</i>.","Ethiopian: from the personal name <i>Lemma</i>, which is interpreted as e.g. ‘he prospered’ in the Amharic language. — Note: Since Ethiopians do not have hereditary surnames, this name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Lemas","meanings":["Spanish: plural form of   Lema  ."]}]},{"name":"Herald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. There has been some confusion with   Gerard .  It died out in England at the end of the 13th century. However, it continued to be popular in Ireland, where it had been brought in the 12th century at the time of Strongbow's invasion. It was used in England in the 17th century and revived in the 19th century, along with several other long-extinct names of Norman, Old English, and Celtic origin, and is now more common than <i>Gerard</i>, which survived all along as an English ‘gentry’ name."],"variants":[{"name":"Jerrold","meanings":["Rare variant of   Gerald  , probably a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Herald de Leca , Lord - 1st, keeper of Stanton was born about 1105, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Henricus de Leca, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Henricus de Leca, was 21. He married Macbeath Macauslan before 1125, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1105–":"umbes 1105–Surnud","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1085–Female":"1085–Surnud","1080":"1080","before 1125":"enne 1125","1127":"1127","1105":"1105","1104":"1104","1125":"1125","about 1127":"umbes 1127","about 1125":"umbes 1125","aproximadamente 1105":"umbes 1105","1085":"1085","The Lennox, Dunbartonshire